# Create dummy variable for whether zipcode is in Seattle or not

  mutate(Seattle = case_when(zipcode >= 98101 & zipcode <= 98119 ~ 1, 
                             zipcode == 98121 | zipcode == 98122 ~ 1, 
                             zipcode >= 98124 & zipcode <= 98126 ~ 1,

  labs(x="Location", y="Proportion of the 'Good View Index'", title="", fill='Good View Index') + scale_x_discrete(name='Location', labels=c('1' = 'Seattle', '0' = 'Elsewhere in King County')) +  scale_fill_discrete( labels=c('0' = 'No view', '1' = 'Fair', '2' = 'Average', '3' = 'Good', '4' = 'Excellent'))

Seattle has a larger proportion of the good views (rated 2, 3 and 4, being highest) than elsewhere in King County, as expected. We expected this as Seattle has city views and the bay and Lake Washington (AKA coastline of the Pugen sound).

view v. waterfront

ggplot(train, aes(x=as.factor(view), fill=as.factor(waterfront)))+
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + labs(x="Good View Index", y="Proportion", title="", fill='Waterfront View?') +  scale_fill_discrete( labels=c('1' = 'Yes', '0' = 'No'))

As expected, the Good View Index and Waterfront view are correlated, and may result in a multicolinearity issue in our model. It is highly likely we should only include one of these predictors - a hypothesis test should be conducted.

Checking assumptions

library(tidyr)
##store fitted y & residuals
yhat<-result$fitted.values
res<-result$residuals
train <- train %>% drop_na(sqft_living) ##store fitted y & residuals yhat<-result$fitted.values res<-result$residuals
##add to data frame
Data<-data.frame(train,yhat,res)
ggplot(Data, aes(x=yhat,y=res))+
geom_point()+
geom_hline(yintercept=0, color="red")+
labs(x="Fitted y", y="Residuals", title="Residual Plot")

The residuals should be evenly scattered on both sides of the red horizontal line, as we move from left to right. We see this in the residual plot, so assumption 1 is met.

The vertical spread of the residuals should be constant as we move from left to right. The spread seems to have a fanning out pattern which makes it inconsistent. Therefore assumption 2 is violated and we might elect to transform our model.

The distribution with a tail will have both the ends of the Q-Q plot to deviate from the straight line and its center follows a straight line. The tail means that compared to the normal distribution there is much more data located at the extremes of the distribution and less data in the center of the distribution.

Section 4: Logistic Regression Model

For our initial, “full” model, we will include the following variables:

Response:
- Seattle: whether the home is in Seattle (1), or elsewhere in King County (0)

Predictors:
- waterfront: whether the apartment was overlooking the waterfront (1) or not (0)
- price: price of each home sold ($)
- sqft_lot: square footage of the land space
- condition: an index from 1 to 5 on the condition of the apartment
- bedrooms: # of bedrooms*
- bathrooms: # of bathrooms, where .5 accounts for a room with a toilet but no shower*
- view: an index from 0 to 4 of how good the view of the property was**
- sqft_above: the square footage of the interior housing space that is above ground level**,

where ** indicates a potential multicolinearity issue, and * indicates a potential interaction term.

Assumptions:
- Observations are independent.
- Response variable is a Bernoulli random variable, with: \(P(y_i = 1) = \pi_i\) and \(P(y_i = 0) = 1 - \pi_i\)

Fit the initial FULL model

train = subset(train, select = -c(id) )
train$Seattle <- as.factor(train$Seattle)
train$waterfront <- as.factor(train$waterfront)
train$view <- as.factor(train$view)
train$condition <- as.factor(train$condition)
initial <- glm(formula=Seattle ~ waterfront + price + sqft_lot + condition + bedrooms + bathrooms + sqft_above + view, family=binomial, data=train)

# P-Value
pval <- 1-pchisq(test_stat, 7)
print(paste('P-Value:', pval))
## [1] "P-Value: 0"

The ∆G2 test statistic in this scenario is the difference in the residual deviances of both models. So we reject the null hypothesis, and prefer the inital, 8-predictor model over the reduced predictor model

Based on these analysis’, we will carry on with the full model.

Odds, Log Odds, and Prediction of a Specific Home

For sake of example, our client is looking for their dream home. Ideally, wants to live in Seattle. Given her preferences, what are the log odds the house she’s looking for is in Seattle? She wants:

  • A waterfront view
  • An ideal price of $660,000
  • At least a small yard for her dog to play in, so an approximate sqft_lot size of 2,000 square feet
  • A home in good (4) condition
  • 2 bedrooms - one for her, one for guests
  • 2 full bathrooms
  • Roughly 1,000 square feet above ground (sqft_above)
  • An excellent (4) view
client<-data.frame(waterfront='Waterfront', 
                   price=660000, 
                   sqft_lot=2000, 
                   condition=4, 
                   bedrooms=2, 
                   bathrooms=2, 
                   sqft_above=1000, 
                   view='4')
predict(initial2, client)
##        1 
## 2.324848

The log odds of the home she’s looking for being in Seattle is 2.324848.

# Convert to odds
odds<-exp(predict(initial2, client))
#odds

paste('Log odds:', 2.324848)
## [1] "Log odds: 2.324848"
paste('Odds:', 10.22512)
## [1] "Odds: 10.22512"
paste('Probability:', 0.9109141)
## [1] "Probability: 0.9109141"
# Convert odds to probability 
prob<-odds/(1+odds)
prob
##         1 
## 0.9109141

The corresponding odds is 10.22512, and the corresponding probability is 0.9109141!
